{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_ilia_ver01/data/sn87055779/00271740438/1929111001/0476.xml":{"full_text":"The Balance of\nDemand and Supply 1\nin our\n\nbrings\nCOMPLETE\nSATISFACTION\nDEMAND\n.Wants of every kind are satisfied\neasily and economically through the\nvaried offers of service and merchan\ndise which appear daily in the Classi\nfied Section.\nEverything is arranged and indexed\nso simply and conveniently that to\nfind and compare the different offers\nof any kind is just as easy a matter\nas it is to look up a number in the\ntelephone directory.\nSUPPLY\nOffers of all\u2019kinds of merchandise\nor service result in quick profits\u2014\nwithout expensive commissions\u2014if\nads are placed in the Classified Sec\ntion.\nReaders in search of any particular\narticle or service all look carefully\nover the offers listed under the ap\npropriate heading each day. They;\ngive their careful attention to classi\nfied ads.\nBuyers and Sellers\nBoth have the advantage\nwhen they\nMeet Directly\nthrough the\nNEWS-TIMES\nCLASSIFIED\nTOURISTS BOOST\nFRENCH INCOME\nWITH BIG SUMS\n\nBusiness Brings $400.\nI 000,000 Into Cities\nof| France.\ni\nBy MINOTT SAUNDERS\nNEA Service Writer\nPARIS, Nov. 9.\u2014After one of the!\nmost successful tourist seasons since\nthe war, it is now estimated that this\ntourist business brings 10,000,000,000\nfrancs ($400,000,000) into Prance an- j\nnually.\nWhat is more, this business has be\ncome a very important factor in'\nFrench trade estimates, so much so\nthat everything possible will be\ndone to encourage it. This money is\na vital item of revenue because\nFrench exports show a deficit of\nnearly 20 per cent over imports,\n\u201cInvisible Exports\u201d\nM. Jules Perquel, editor of \u201cLe\nCapital\u201d and a recognized expert in\nregard to the French international ac\ncounts, giving the figure of ten billion\nfrancs as tourist expenditure here,\nclassifies this sum as \"invisible ex\nports.\u201d M. Meynial, in his annual\nstudy of the French balance o\u2019 ac\ncounts for 1928, places the figure at\nnine billion, but the Office National\ndu Tourisme agrees with M. Perquel,\nputting it at ten.\nDr. Cany, president of the Federa\ntion des Syndicats d\u2019Intitiative du\nMassif Central\u2014the French Midlands\n\u2014estimates that the average foreign\ntourist\u2019s expenditure in France should\nbe regarded as distributed as follows:\nTwenty per cent in hotel expenses;\n20 per cent in transport of various\nkinds; 20 per cent for amusements;\n23 per cent in purchases in the stores,\nand 14 per cent in petty expenditure,\nsuch as cabs, postages, telegrams, etc.\nTravel agencies estimate that about\n750,000 British and 230,000 Americans\nare now visiting France annually, but\nthese only constitute a proportion\u2014\nalthough certainly the most important\none\u2014of the total. With the return of\nprosperity in Central Europe, the\nnumber of German, Italian, Czecho\nslovakian and Scandinavian visitors\nis increasing each year.\nSees Prosperity\nM. Perquel further estimates that\ntourist traffic since the war has been\nworth 50 billion francs to France and\nthat this business is an important\nconsideration for the prosperity of the\ncountry.\nOther interesting tourist statistics\nare found in the reports of visitors to\nvarious museums, which always at\ntract tourists. During the three sum\nmer months this year 196.332 men,\nwomen and children visited the Lou\nvre, which is an increase by nearly\na thousand over 1928. Admission fees\namounted to 1.042,164 francs, the\nhighest sum taken in by any French\nmuseum. Second in line was the\nChauteau of Versailles, where 616,437\nfrancs were paid by visitors. Mont\nSaint-Michel, on the Brittany coast,\nwas third in popularity, taking in\n119 684 francs, while Sainte Chapelle,\nfamous chapel in the courtyard of\nthe Palais de Justice in Paris, took\nin 318,763 francs.\nFees Go to Monuments\nThese sums are subject to a de\nduction to cover expenses and the\nnet sum is then turned over to the na\ntional fund for liistorial monuments.\nThe sums taken in by all monuments\nand museums amounted to 5,657,980\nfrancs, of which the muesum fund re\nceived a little over three million.\nThe museum directors report that\nAmerican and English visitors are\nshowing an increased interest in the\nmuseums, which they consider a trib\nute to French art.\nnarcwri\nCampfire Girls\ni\nHeadquarters will aid any group In\ngetting in touch with needy families,\nMrs. Armstrong announces. Camp\nFire Girls are expected to prepare\nbaskets for Thanksgiving, she stated.\nGuardians\u2019 Meeting\n7*he November meeting of the\nGliardians\u2019 association will be held on\nWednesday evening, at 7:30 o\u2019clock at\nheadquarters. Important matters for\nthe City Council Fire are to be dis\ncussed.\nDon\u2019t Forget\nThe Bread Wrappers must be fas\ntened together in order to insure your\nreceiving credit for them.\nWe have only 23 days before the\nend of the Big Hop. Mrs. M. B. Dii\nley has just started a new group at\nthe First Presbyterian church and\ncredit for the organization of the new\ngroup goe3 to the members of the\nAkiho group with their Guardian,\nMiss Dorothy Eldredge. Miss Isobel\nFlett has a new group at the Riley\nschool.\nClasses in \u201cChristmas-craft\u201d are\nstarting this week at Headquarters.\nThe first, meeting will be on Tuesday\nafternoon after school and will con\ntinue every day for the next two\nweeks.\nThe long list of Local Honors\nprinted in this paper last week Is\nopen to all and you may earn one or\nany number of them. Simply have\nsome one O. K. your honor and bring\nit in to Headquarters to be recorded.\nGlee Club and Princess Meet\nWork has already been started on\nthe all-city program as a result of\nthe princess meeting on Friday of last\nweek. Plans have been made for the\nelection of city officers and next\nweek we shall print the program and\nofficers. Miss Bernice Axtell met with\na large number of girls who came out\nior the first try-out for the Camp\nFire Glee club. When the officers\nhave been elected and the operetta\nhas been chosen definite plans will be\nannounced.\nAkiho\nWe oper.ed oiir meeting by singing\nthe Law of the Fire. During the\nbusiness meeting we discussed honors\nand practiced bandaging. We closed\nour meeting by singing Burn, Fire\nBum. HELEN CAULEY.\nCheshchamay\nThe Cheschamay group had a\nlovely Halloween party last week in\nthe Central Junior High school. The\ncostumes were original and Ruth\nWright won the prize with her orien\ntal costume. Prizes in other contests\nwere won by Rose Cserpea, Florence\nCebulskt and Virginia Vieczorzk. Re\nfreshments were served by Madelyn\nMorehouse, Thelma Fields and Marie\nWilke.\nThursday we held a regular busl\nClassified $\\ds Bring Results\u2014-\u2014\ni\nw\no\nQB\n1 Day a Day\u00bb [fl-7 Day*\n.54:$\ni U'oiS\n1S-M\n24-30\n30-3#\n30-42\n42-48\n.72\n.90\n1.08\n1.20\n1.44\n.floi 1.88\n.81| 2.10\n,9W 2.52\n1.14 2.94\n1.30- 3.301 3.00\n1.62i 8.3#\n1.80\n2.27\n4.20\n0.04\n2.83 3.88\n3.72\n3.03\n3.78)\n4.54\n5.30\n6.06\nCOCNT 6 WORDS TO THE LIN*.\nTon receive the cash rata on all charge\nads paid within six days.\nCLASSIFIED ADVERTISING\nINFORMATION.\nAll ad* are restricted to thalr proper\nclassification, The publishers reserve tha\nright to edit <.t reject any classified\ncopy.\nAdvertising ordered for Irregular In\nlertlont takes the o\u20ace-tIme rale. No ad\nIs taken on a basis of less than 18 words.\nAds ordered for seven times and stop\nped before expiration will b\u00ab charged\nfor only the number of times tha ad ap\npeared. end adjustment made at the\nrata earned.\nSpecial rates for yearly advertising\nUpon request.\nCareful attention given to mstl orders.\nWHEN AND WHERE TO SLAC*\nTOUR ADS.\nThe Classified Advertising Department\nu located at cornet Colfax Ate. and\nMain St.\nThese office* are open to receive ad\nvertising from 7:30 a. m. to 6 p. m. dally.\nSaturday till 0 p. m.\nIn event of error tn advertisement\ntome should be reported Immediately.\nThe Ad Taker will gladly assstt you\nIf desired, so that the copy Is prepared\nIn such a manner at to bring the great\nest results for you.\nTO CANCEL YOUR ADD CALL THE\nCANCELLATION CLERK\u20148-2121.\nThe South Bend News-Times Is\nmember of the Association of News\npaper Classified Advertising Mana\ngers, which has for Its aim the elimi\nnation of fraudulent and misleading\nadvertising. The NEWS-TIMES en\ndeavors to print only truthful classi\nfied ads and will appreciate the call\ning of its attention to any advertising\nnot conforming to these standards.\nANNOUNCEMENTS\nBtrayed\u2014Lost\u2014Found.\nIK THE person who took overcoat by\nmistake at Progress Club Dance Friday\nnight will Inform Bruce Brown, 008\nColfax, no questions asked.\nbills;\nLOST\u2014Twenty-five dollars, bills; be\ntween Moss Cigar Store and Associates\nBarber Shop, West JefTerson. Be\nward. Tel. 3-2197 or 8-4775.__\nLOST\nBLACK POLICE DOO\nCall 3-2843\nLOST\u2014Books containing valuable papers,\nby 1st house north of Cleveland Bead\nDy ssi uuunc iiuiiu '-\u2018Y, f t,;\non Ironwood road, or on Margaret St.,\nentering Mishawaka. Only valuable to\nowner. Beward. Call News-Times\nClassified Dept.\nLOST\u2014A case with stereoptlcon or lan\ntern slide projector on Colfax Ave., or\nEsther St., Thursday morning. Finder\nplease notify Dr. L. F. Fisher, 820\nSherland Bldg. Thone 2-1729. Beward.\nness meeting at which our princess,\nPeggy Lang, presided. After roll call,\nsecretary\u2019s reports, the secretary\nread a letter from Headquarters.\nThree of our girls decided to try out\nfor the Glee club and our princess\nand another member are attending\nthe potluek supper Friday night at\nHeadquarters. We decided we would\nall try to save as many bread wrap\npers as we possibly could. We voted\nto sell candy to make up a deficit of\n$2,23. To close the meeting we learn\ned a new song, \"The Indian Trail.\u201d\nJUNE IVES.\nFirst M. E. Church\nWe have started a new group at\nthe First M. E. church with Miss Elva\nRuth Holem as our Guardian The\nofficers of the group are: Esther\nLemons, princess; Ruth Lemons,\nvice-princess; Roberta Frame, secre\ntary-treasurer, and Elizabeth Ginz,\nscribe. At our last business meeting\nwe chose our names, discussed the\nprincess meeting and planned a pot\nluck supper for our next meeting. We\nwill meet again next Tuesday at 4\no\u2019clock. ELIZABETH GINZ.\nLuta Koda Sisters\nWe held our regular meeting at the\nhome of our Guardian and discussed\na way to earn money for the new\ncamp site. We also decided to give a\nThanksgiving basket to a poor family.\nFollowing the business meeting we\nplayed games and the meeting was\nadjourned. WINIFRED MUNGER.\nNawakwa\nAt our regular business meeting\nwe planned a hike for next Saturday\nand a Council Fire for our next roeet\n1 ing. The meeting was adjourned\nwith a few camp songs.\nMAE EICHLER.\nBbulnala\nWe bet at the home of our Guar\ndian, Mrs. Nennen for a short busi\nness meeting. We opened the meet\ning by singing \u201cWohelo for Aye\u201d, and\nthe Law. The bread wrapper con\ntest was discussed and Mary Alice\nBush gave a brief report on the Field\nAid Course she recently completed.\nOur guardian told us about the va\nI rious courses to be offered at Head\nquarters and we closed the meeting\nby singing Mammy Moon and repeat\ning the Camp Fire Benediction.\nMARY ALICE BUSH.\nTanda\nWe opened our meeting by singing\nthe \u201cLaw of the Fire\u201d. We discussed\nhonors we are going to win, the Wood\nGatherer\u2019s rank we are working for\nand the ceremonial we are going to\nhave soon. ALMA FORD.\nTumaga\nxne lumaga group met in nwm\n115 of the Riley school with 19 girls\nand our guardian present. Durfhg\nthe short business meeting, we found\nthat the Pottawattomie tribe Is lead\ning in the bread wrapper contest and\nwe are planning on a Plre Maker\u2019s\ndinner at Potawatomi park Satur\nday If the weather permits. Follow\ning the business meeting, we enjoyed\nan Armistice day program arranged\nby our princess, Dorothy Wickman.\nThe program Is as follows: \u2018\u2018Pledge\nof Allegiance to the Flag; song, \u201cThe\nStar Spangled Banner\u201d; \u201cHistory of\nthe Star Spangled Banner\", by\nWaneta Butterbaugh; song, \u201cAmer\nica\u201d; \u201cCredo\u201d by Evelyn Dunnuck;\npoem, \u201cIn Flander\u2019s Fields\u201d, by Kath\nryn Ann Pabst; song, \u201cAmerica the\nBeautiful\u201d; song, \u201cAmerica for Thee\",\nby Mary Wickman: \u201cHistory of the\nBattle Hymn of the Republic\", by\nJeanette Hoglund; song, \u201cThe Battle\nHymn of the Republic\u201d; the Camp\nI Fire Benediction.\nNettopew\nI We opened our meeting with a song\nwhich was followed by the roll call\nand the scribe\u2019s report. After a short\nbusiness meeting which consisted of\nplanning a council fire, we\u2018were en\ntertained with games and contests.\nPrizes were awarded Vanda Wells,\nEvelyn Welborn and Mary Weiss. We\nadjourned the meeting by singing,\n\"The Sun Is Sinking in the West.\u201d\nBONNIE STRADLEY.\nCLASSIFICATION INDEX\nANNOUNCEMENTS\n2\u2014 Strayed\u2014Lo at\u2014Found\n3\u2014 Personal\n\u2666\u2014Travel Opportunities\n6\u2014In Memorlam\n6\u2014 Card of Thank*\n7\u2014 Funeral Director*\n\u00bb\u2014Florists\n9\u2014Cemetery Lot*. Monument*\n19\u2014Announcement!\u2014Mlec*ll4n*ott*\nEMPLOYMENT\n11\u2014Female Help Wanted\n13\u2014 Positions Wanted\u2014Female\n14\u2014 Male Help Wanted\n15\u2014 Position* Wanted\u2014Male\n16\u2014 Male or Female Help Wanted\n17\u2014 Salesmen and Agent*\nIS\u2014Schools\u2014Instruction __\nBUSINESS SERVICE\n19\u2014 Beauty Parlors\n20\u2014 Registered PodtatrUt\n21\u2014 D re s sin a k log\u2014Millinery\n22\u2014 Plano Tuning\n23\u2014 Business Service Ottered\n24\u2014 Building\u2014Contracting\n25\u2014 Painting\u2014Papering\n26\u2014 Heating\u2014Plumbing\n27\u2014 Transfer\u2014Storage\n28\u2014 Repairing\n29\u2014 Cleaning and Dyeing\n31\u